DIRB
Web content scanner for hidden directories and files

Web Application
Description
DIRB is a web content scanner that looks for existing web objects by launching a dictionary-based attack against a web server. It finds hidden directories, backup files, and other sensitive content.

Installation / Check
Check if installed:

which dirb
Install command:

sudo apt install dirb
Basic Syntax
dirb <url> [wordlist]
Common Commands
Command	What it does	When to use	Risk
dirb http://192.168.1.1

Basic scan with default wordlist	Quick discovery of common directories	
dirb http://192.168.1.1 /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt

Scan with larger wordlist	More thorough directory discovery	
dirb http://192.168.1.1 -o results.txt

Save results to file	For documentation and later review	
dirb http://192.168.1.1 -a "Mozilla/5.0"

Custom user agent	To avoid detection by user-agent filters	
dirb http://192.168.1.1 -X .php,.html,.txt

Search specific extensions	Finding files with specific extensions	
Step-by-Step Guide
1
Identify target web server
2
Run basic scan: dirb http://target
3
Wait for scan completion
4
Review found directories
5
Investigate interesting paths
6
Try with different wordlists for better coverage
Understanding the Output
DIRB shows discovered URLs with their response codes. CODE:200 means found, CODE:403 means forbidden (exists but access denied).

Important Warnings
•
Only scan websites you own or have permission to test
•
Scans generate lots of web server logs
•
May trigger WAF or IDS alerts
⚠️ Use Kali Linux tools only on systems you own or have written permission to test. Unauthorized hacking is illegal and can result in criminal charges.
